We analyzed the surface functional groups and elemental valence bond structures of the synthesized materials using FT-IR spectroscopy. As displayed in Fig. 2
                        a, the characteristic peaks at 3280, 2941, and 1649 cm−1 are attributed to the stretching vibrations of –OH/NH2, −C–H, and C=O, respectively. To analyze the surface elemental composition of the synthesized material further, we also used XPS spectroscopy to investigate. As shown in Fig. 2b, the synthetic material mainly comprises three elements, C, N, and O, with element percentages of 46.81, 2.37, and 50.82 %, respectively. As displayed in Fig. 2c, the three characteristic peaks in the high-resolution C 1s XPS spectra correspond to −C–C/C=C (284.79 eV), −C–O (286.39 eV), and −C=O/C=N (287.69 eV) bonds, respectively [8,21]. The two fitted peaks in the high-resolution N 1s XPS spectra are attributed to pyridine N (398.99 eV) and pyrrole N (400.29 eV) (Fig. 2d) [22]. The two characteristic peaks in the high-resolution O 1s XPS spectra correspond to −C=O (532.39 eV) and –C–O/O–H (533.09 eV), respectively (Fig. 2e) [15]. These results agree with the FT-IR spectroscopy analysis, indicating that multiple nitrogen- and oxygen-containing functional groups exist on the surface of the multi-wavelength emission fluorescent N-doped CDs, which leads to the synthesized materials exhibiting better physicochemical properties. Optical properties are a prerequisite for applying and developing synthetic materials, so we explored the UV–vis absorption spectra and optical properties of multi-wavelength emission fluorescent N-doped CDs using steady-state and transient fluorescence spectrometers. As displayed in Fig. S1, the UV–vis spectra of the N-doped CDs exhibit three different absorption peaks at 266, 314, and 374 nm, the first two of which correspond to the π-π* transition of C=N [16], while the latter one is attributed to the n-π* transition of C=O [16,23]. In addition, the fluorescence emission peaks of the N-doped CDs are gradually red-shifted with the increase of the excitation wavelength, exhibiting the optical properties of multi-wavelength emission fluorescence (Fig. 2f). Therefore, we chose the excitation wavelengths of 350, 400, and 470 nm to analyze the fluorescence lifetimes of the N-doped CDs (Figs. S2, S3, S4, S5 and Table 1
                        ), and found that the average lifetimes changed from 1.18 ns to 6.87 ns and then to 5.98 ns with the increase of excitation wavelength, and the percentage of τ2 increased from 11.67 % to 77.01 % and then to 75.25 %. And, we further measured the fluorescence quantum yield of the CDs and found that the value is 8.45 % (Ex = 350 nm), 12.41 % (Ex = 400 nm) and 10.62 % (Ex = 470 nm), indicating that N-doped CDs have excellent photoluminescence optical properties at the excitation wavelength of 400 nm (Table S1) [24].
